			</tr>
		</table></td><td class="PanelBody" valign="Top"><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3" border="0" width="100%">
			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Amateur Trak Homework to be graded and corrected please<a name="56913"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 16 04 11:41 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Wila,
<br />

<br />
Here's a few tidbits of knowledge (below) that I've collected from my two encounters with Trak and also from reading the forums here and at TCH.
<br />

<br />
Firstly, don't forget to buy Peridots, Pearls, coffins, and EEs (if you have necros and you think you will need them for rezzing the clerics).  Buy twice as many pearls as you think you will need (assuming you have mage(s) for CoTH).  CoTH is AWESOME for getting raid force down to Lair (we fought single group down to lair and CoTH'd the rest of the raid force into lair).  Using CoTH to summon folks back from banishment at shrooms is an ideal situation too, obviously.
<br />

<br />
The benefit to using single group to fight down to lair and CoTH'ing the rest (still assuming you have a mage to help, and don't forget that somebody will need to stay back at zone-in for inviting folks into group for CoTH) is that you won't have folks wandering off and getting lost on the way down.  This invariably happens whenever you move a raid force through a dungeon zone like OS.  The route down to lair isn't a simple one for folks to follow if they don't know the way by-heart.
<br />

<br />
I assume you will be leading the raid.  If so, try not to complicate your strategy too much.  There is a ton of good info above in your post, but most of it you can keep to yourself and not have to impart to your raid force.  The less you have to tell them strat-wise, the less confused they will be.  Simplicity is golden.  Why is it the case here?  Because if all goes well, you will burn Trak down in 20-40 seconds flat.  You should still be gtg up to 60 secs.  If the fight stretches past 60 seconds, the odds of winning grow exponentially against you.
<br />

<br />
The main advice to give your casters is, &quot;Get into melee range and start burning Trak down for all you are worth.  Overburn his draconic arse off&quot;.  The main advice to give your melee DPS'ers is, &quot;Get into melee range and smack Trak silly!  Smack him down like he owes you money!&quot;.
<br />

<br />
Now, specifically to some of the bullets in your post:
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">hopefully find a druid who will work with me on the eye of zomm trick</span></blockquote>
<br />
I'm a little confused here.  If you've got a SS Helm or a goodly supply of Stalking Probes, you can check Trak's Lair on your own.  You shouldn't need a druid's help.  Just keep summoning an eye while you are facing flat against a wall at OS zone-in.  Once you see that your eye has popped into the vacinity of Trak's lair, use the bind-sight song to change your view to a Jugg.  Leap-frog your view from Jugg to Jugg (may have to use camera views and swing out a bit).  Eventually, you can get your sight bound to Tolapumj (Jumpy) or, even better, the Sebilite Protector (huge Jugg).  Once you have bound sight to either of these two, you will be able to see whether Real Trak or UDB is up.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">First we clear the Lair of Juggernauts and other named folks. This should be done in concert by a Monk/Bard combo methinks. 
<br />
</span></blockquote>
<br />
We cleared with just me lull-pulling singles down to the bridge area.  Make sure your melee'ers push mobs back in toward the rock wall away from the Lair, though, having to dive into the water to finish off mobs is a pain.  Once lair is cleared, I would suggest moving your raid force up top and then into the &quot;Trak Cubby Hole&quot;.  I don't know what else to call it, but you will see what I mean once you are there.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">For the Undead Bard fight, leave the casters out of it. Let only melee fight the undead bard.</span></blockquote>
<br />
He's a wimp.  Smack him down any way you like.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">The first thing Trak 2.0 will do is banish the first person with aggro.</span></blockquote>
<br />
If you've got an SK, have them HT or Super HT Trak as the very first action of ANYBODY.  The SK will likely get banished first, and they can FD at shroms.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">If we do not have a CotH Mage then that person will either have to run back from the Mushroom Forest or take one for the team. I am thinking a Bard with Fading Memories can do this, but am not sure. </span></blockquote>
<br />
IMO, it's not a good idea for anybody to try to run back from shrooms.  If you don't have a CoTH mage, and the banished person can't FD, Fade, Escape (Rogue), etc., then they may just have to &quot;take one for the team&quot;.
<br />

<br />
*Important* - If I were you, I'd not plan on twisting more than 3 songs.  Besides the reasons of our horrendous fizzle rate lately, you want to make ABSOLUTELY sure that AoE resists don't drop.  If you are successful in this, hardly anybody will get DoT'd.  Equip your drum.  If you have a necro there, have him/her DMF everyone before UDB turn-in.  The resists on DMF are awesome when added to your own AoE resist song.  I would avoid substituting in PoV unless you are ABSOLUTELY POSITIVE there will be adequate bards present to be members of EVERY group.  I would still lean toward avoiding PoV altogether.  If multiple bards are present, there is a lot to bbe said for all of them singing AoE resists concurently.  Less chance of resists dropping unexpectedly.
<br />

<br />
If you do decide to do AoE resists, having a bard in the Tank group isn't really essential.  Cleric, CoTH mage, Back-up Healer, Melee, Melee, Melee would be better.  Create a second group based upon you singing Muse to amplify DD and DoT damage of casters.  Better bang for your buck here, IMO.  Create your third group with whatever you have left.
<br />

<br />
We didn't really think to do this, so I'm not sure how effective it will be, but if you have Shammy's and/or Clerics that have Radiant Cure, this would probably help out a TON on anybody that ends up with DoT after fight.
<br />

<br />
That brings up another point, I wouldn't focus on curing folks' DoTs until Trak is down.  Have it be one of your first priorities as soon as Trak drops, yes, but drop him first.
<br />

<br />
As soon as Trak drops, do this (in order):
<br />
1.  Loot.  Your gut strings are the reason you are here.  Get them looted right away.  Loot the BP too.  It's droppable, you can have the raid roll on it as soon as cleanup is done.
<br />
2.  Move folks back into &quot;Trak Cubby Hole&quot;.  Juggs will be re-spawning soon.  You want to be away from the spawn points if possible (just to avoid confusion).
<br />
3.  Cure Trak's DoTs on anybody unfortunate enough to have been afflicted.
<br />
4.  CoTH back the banished (who are at shrooms).
<br />
5.  Summon corpses from shrooms (hopefully there will be none, but you never know).
<br />
6.  Rezz Mana-regen'ers.
<br />
7.  Rezz additional clerics.
<br />
8.  Rezz anybody else.
<br />
9.  Roll on the BP.
<br />
10.  Thank everybody for coming.  Don't feel like you have to be reserved, you will be VERY excited!  It will be infectious!  This is good!  Boil over with excitement, and don't hide it!  *grin*
<br />
11.  Arange for transport out.  If druids/wizzies can't get everybody out at once, have wizzies TL the extras first.  Alternatively, have druid/wizzie bind in cubby hole and ferry folks out.
<br />
12.  Before going to do your final turn-ins, send EACH and EVERY member of your raid force a personal TELL and let them know how much you appreciate their contribution.  Personalize your tell with how you think they SPECIFICALLY helped the raid succeed.  It's just the right thing to do, and it's NICE.  <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" /> 
<br />
13.  Do final turn-ins.  Call me paranoid, but on something this important, ALWAYS hail the NPC first to make sure they aren't in some kind of whacky suspended mode (don't laugh, I've seen it happen).  Give them a nebulous item like a single food or drink.  They SHOULD hand it back to you.  This will sort of &quot;reset&quot; them.  You never know what kind of garbage somebody else before you has handed them.  Re-Hail the NPC and then do your turn-ins.
<br />

<br />
There are a thousand ways to do this encounter successfully, so, obvously, your mileage may vary, but I believe what I've told you above is a STRONG recipe for success!
<br />

<br />
If I'm not there to help, Wila, GL!  Properly executed, though, you will need no luck whatsoever.  <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-2.gif" border="0" alt="Big Smile" hspace="2" /> 
<br />

<br />
</span></td>
